cious external code.","paths":["A malicious or misconfigured `TARGET` returns an unexpected token from `aave()` and/or an attacker-controlled contract from `pool()`","`_prepareNonZeroAaveInput()` spends 1 ETH on the returned token and approves it for `TARGET`","The verifier later calls `withdraw()` on the returned pool address and cannot distinguish the fake dependency from the intended one"],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"One-second AMM deadlines make the strategy trivially censorable","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:141","FlawVerifier.sol:154"],"claim":"Both swaps use `block.timestamp + 1` as the deadline, leaving almost no inclusion slack and making successful execution depend on near-immediate block inclusion.","impact":"Normal congestion or deliberate builder/validator delay can cause the swaps to expire and revert, creating an easy denial-of-service condition for a time-sensitive execution path.","paths":["Broadcast `executeOnOpportunity()`","The transaction lands more than one second after submission","One of the swaps reverts because the deadline has expired"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Unlimited AAVE approval to TARGET can expose all verifier inventory","locations":["FlawVerifier.sol:111","FlawVerifier.sol:156"],"claim":"When the zero-input deposit path fails, `_prepareNonZeroAaveInput()` grants `TARGET` a max allowance over the verifier's AAVE and never revokes or scopes it to the intended single-unit deposit amount.","impact":"If `TARGET` can ever invoke `transferFrom()` itself, or expose any path that does so, it can sweep not just the 1-unit seed deposit but the verifier's entire current and future AAVE balance, including bought inventory and withdrawn rewards.","paths":["Trigger the fallback branch once so `_prepareNonZeroAaveInput()` executes","The verifier leaves `IERC20(aave).approve(TARGET, type(uint256).max)` in place indefinitely","`TARGET` later uses the allowance to pull AAVE from the verifier beyond the intended deposit amount"],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Hardcoded dependency addresses are used without any chain or code validation","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"This mainly relies on wrong-network deployment or external address replacement outside the verifier's intended mainnet environment, so it is better treated as deployment/configuration risk than a reportable in-protocol vulnerability."},{"title":"Native-balance profit check can be spoofed by unsolicited ETH transfers","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"An unsolicited ETH transfer increases the verifier's real balance only because the sender pays that subsidy themselves; it does not create a realistic theft, insolvency, or protocol-level loss scenario."},{"title":"Counter state is completely unauthenticated","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`Counter.sol` is a standalone toy contract with no privileged role, funds, or security-sensitive integration shown in scope, so unrestricted setters are not reportable here."}]}
